ed in no less a measure by the delcaration of the earliest Puranas, t=\r\nhat is Vishnu Purana and the SB, that Krshna was a complete Avatara. Some,\n=\r\n like the Gaudiya Vaishnavas, went one step ahead and took a very literal v=\r\niew of it all and declared Krshna as the Ultimate Being, and the formless P=\r\naramatma, as well as Narayana,=C2=A0as merely=C2=A0the aura of Krshna. Rama=\r\n was also intricately linked to this Krshnaa-ism, but was looked at as the =\r\nearlier brith of Krshna, not as a separate Divity in himself.\n=C2=A0\nWhatev=\r\ner the case maybe, each school had its own set of established saints and sc=\r\nholars to vouch for their views. So it boiled down to interpretation, which=\r\n is often, as you rightly pointed out, based on=C2=A0various conditionings.=\r\n\n=C2=A0\nWe=C2=A0human beings are creatures of imagination. Whenever an Avat=\r\nar appears on the earth,=C2=A0most of the great Mahatmas who appear after t=\r\nhe Avatara, remain=C2=A0overawed by the=C2=A0character of the last Avatara=\r\n=C2=A0because invariable in the context of the desh-kaal-patra of those tim=\r\nes, the life of the Avatara shows actions performed which are=C2=A0way beyo=\r\nnd=C2=A0imagination for *those times*. Such a situation continues until the=\r\n next Avatara comes on earth. I am sure in the period after Rama, and befor=\r\ne Krshna, of which we have very little written record, the world at large r=\r\nemained entirely overawed by Rama Avatara.\n=C2=A0\nIn this light Krshna is t=\r\nhe Poorna-Avatara. When Kalki will appear on earth, he will be invarible ac=\r\ncompanied by a set of powerful Rishis - every Avatara comes with his coteri=\r\ne of Rishis who explain the philosophy and spirituality of the Avatara to t=\r\nhe general masses - who will then create new scriptures and Kalki will be l=\r\nooked at as the crest jewel=C2=A0of the Avataras.\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nI believe in the evolutionary parable of these 9 Avatara becau=\r\nse I find no other reason why these set of Avatara, from the whole list of =\r\npossible=C2=A0Avataras, have captured the popular imagination. I mean Datta=\r\ntreya is an Avatara too as per SB. His spirituality is no less than that of=\r\n any other Avatara. Yet, he is not in the list of 9/10 Avataras. \n=C2=A0\nTh=\r\ne=C2=A0original Nath Yogis used to consider=C2=A0Nine Chakras in the Human =\r\nBody. The idea of Kundalini Yoga also came from them, which was basically e=\r\nxploring=C2=A0cronologically all these nine chakras one after the other by =\r\nflooding them with Chit-Shakti.\n=C2=A0\nThere are 9 basic grahas in jyotish.=\r\n Each graha could very well=C2=A0represent the essential nature of each cha=\r\nkra. All these make me more sanguine that there must be Nine Evolutionary A=\r\nvataras, not ten. In which case Kalki must be the Ninth Avatara.\n=C2=A0\nBud=\r\ndha, as you rightly pointed out,=C2=A0has a tremendous logical appeal in Ka=\r\nli Yuga. But if logic is the criteria, then why not Adi Shankara? I may not=\r\n agree to=C2=A0his philosophy as it comes down to us from his followers, bu=\r\nt it cannot be denied that=C2=A0Adi Shankara was=C2=A0arguable one of the s=\r\nharpest and most logical of spiritual philosphers. His intellectual and log=\r\nical mind=C2=A0is beyond doubt.=C2=A0Just that Shankara=C2=A0never claimed =\r\nhimself to be an Avatara. Neither did=C2=A0Siddhartha. Only that the later =\r\ncame 3000 years ago, and the former came possibly in the last 1000 years.=\r\n=C2=A0Shankara&#39;s spiritual impact on the world is no less than that of the=\r\n=C2=A0Buddha. What mainstream=C2=A0Hinduism today is, could not have been, =\r\nhad it not been for the invaluable contribution of Adi Shankara. And if Bud=\r\ndha was truly=C2=A0the awaited=C2=A09th Avatara of Vishnu, Shankara would n=\r\not have been able to absorb the philosophy of Buddha into Hinduism and thus=\r\n make it lose its grip on India. Buddhism\n barely exists in land of its bir=\r\nth.\n=C2=A0\nAll this taken together, make me more and more convinced that th=\r\nere are 9 evolutionary Avataras and the 9th is yet to come.\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0 =\r\n*=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nA little bit about Rama and Krshna. When I said I admire R=\r\nama, it is not a lip-service. There are incidents in the Ramayana which I f=\r\nind extremely inspiring, educative and uplifting. Like the incident where R=\r\nama was to cross the ocean. Rama knew very well that if he wanted, in one m=\r\noment he could have used his Divine Astras and forced the ocean to yield wa=\r\ny to his army. Yet he sat in silent supplication for days, praying that the=\r\n ocean allow his army safe passage. When all else failed, when genuine good=\r\nwill was not recirpocated, and it was absolutely necessary to cross the oce=\r\nan,=C2=A0THEN=C2=A0Rama took up weapons to get the job done.=C2=A0A powerfu=\r\nl warrior,=C2=A0who knows=C2=A0very well how=C2=A0powerful he=C2=A0himself =\r\nis, not letting that sense of power pervert his mind even for a moment is a=\r\nn amazing phenomenon. This kind of self-control is rare and worthy of comte=\r\nmplation, specially by anyone who feels, ever so slightly, that he/she has =\r\nsome form of power or influence in\n this world in any sphere.=C2=A0Rama had=\r\n no malice for anyone. Not even Ravana, by the end of the war at least. He =\r\nwas the very personification of Satwa. In Satwa, conflict and malice and cu=\r\nnningness are impossible.\n=C2=A0\nRecently, a friend of mine told me that he=\r\n has learnt all his life that one must listen to Krshna&#39;s advice, but only =\r\nfollow what Rama did, and not what Krshna did. I disagree with this vehemen=\r\ntly. If one reads entire Krshna&#39;s life=C2=A0with an objective mind, Krshna =\r\nof Vrndavana, Krshna of Mathura, Krshna of Kurushetra, Krshna the Jagat Gur=\r\nu who speaks the Gita, one will find that what Krshna the Guru adviced in t=\r\nhe Gita,=C2=A0Krshna the=C2=A0Divine Worker=C2=A0himself followed it all th=\r\nrough his life at every instance. It is his=C2=A0perfect detachment under a=\r\nll circumstances of life, from childhood=C2=A0to his death,=C2=A0that makes=\r\n me wonder, was this a man or was this a God? Can a man even do something l=\r\nike this? It is as if there is a part of Krshna who is always separate from=\r\n everything, and silently watches the whole scene with a bemused smile. He =\r\nhad not a single personal stake in the Mahabharata. Rama at least had his w=\r\nife abducted for him to start a war against Ravana.\n But Krshna had zero=C2=\r\n=A0personal stake in the Mahabharata.=C2=A0After liberating his parents fro=\r\nm Kamsa, very soon he went off to meet the Pandavas. From out of nowhere he=\r\n forced himself into the politics of the Mahabharata, and precipitated a gr=\r\neat war to cleanse the world of burden. While Lakshmana devoutly followed R=\r\nama all along the Ramayana and they were like an inseparable pair, as=C2=A0=\r\nBalarama in his next incarnation=C2=A0he could=C2=A0hardly understand Krshn=\r\na. There are so many occassions where Balarama asks Krshna, what are they d=\r\noing with all these kings, and=C2=A0that they should=C2=A0return to their v=\r\nillage in Vrndavana. Krshna merely smiles. He knows that not everyone will =\r\nunderstand everything. But that cannot stop him from following his dharma, =\r\nwith perfect detachement from eveyrthing of this plane. Neither false prais=\r\nes, nor wrong accusations by his close people can affect him one bit. And I=\r\n am not even counting the miracles he perfromed as a Divine Child. So I\n wo=\r\nrship Krshna, because I have not yet met or heard of read of=C2=A0a single =\r\nsadhaka or saint or ordinary man or mahatma=C2=A0who has displayed this kin=\r\nd of perfected detachment through thick and thin, yet not withdrawing from =\r\nthe world or actively performing a larger dharma.\n=C2=A0\nI started apprecia=\r\nting Swami Vivekanada more after I understood a bit of the Krshna Avatara. =\r\nThat was the last known saint who lived a whirlwind life in the middle of a=\r\n circus-stoplight of fame and accusations, on one side adoring admirers and=\r\n on the other bitter enemies accusing him of=C2=A0being a heretic=C2=A0righ=\r\nt upto the=C2=A0very end of his brief life,=C2=A0and yet none of that affec=\r\nted him to any great degree. He faced terrific racism in the America, yet n=\r\not a single speech of his reflects the slightest trace of bitterness, anger=\r\n, or negativity. That is such a fantastic achievement, IMHO.\n=C2=A0\nI agree=\r\n with you, Narasimha, for most of us it is better to=C2=A0try to=C2=A0mould=\r\n ones life=C2=A0with the same kind of supreme selflessness that Rama showed=\r\n all along.=C2=A0Not just worship Rama=C2=A0but more importantly study=C2=\r\n=A0his life and imbibe,=C2=A0to whatever degree possible, the quality he re=\r\npresented.=C2=A0Maybe, just maybe, then the Unmanifested Reality - Shiva - =\r\nwill fix the mind so firmly on that Reality, that in some future life, in s=\r\nome later birth, one will be able to live life like Krshna showed, unattach=\r\ned and unaffected by any dirt that the world throws up. And then the=C2=A0U=\r\nniversal=C2=A0Chit-Shakti (Adya Shakti)=C2=A0will flood such an individual =\r\nwith oppulence unimaginable, of this world and also of=C2=A0what lies in ot=\r\nher worlds, like Krshna&#39;s six oppulences -=C2=A0Infinite wealth, infinite b=\r\neauty, infinite power/knowledge, infinite fame, and infinite detachment fro=\r\nm all the other five. \n=C2=A0\n=C2=A0\nEnjoyed this discussion. :)\n=C2=A0\nJai=\r\n Jai=C2=A0Rama Krshna Hari!\n=C2=A0\n-Regards\n=C2=A0Rajarshi\n=C2=A0\nawaktam w=\r\nyaktimApannam manyantE mAmabuddhayah |param bhAwamajAnanto mamAwyayamanutta=\r\nmam ||[7:24]\n\n\n________________________________\nFrom: Narasimha P.V.R. Rao =\r\n&lt;pvr108@...&gt;\nTo: &quot;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com&quot; &lt;vedic-wisdom@yahoogr=\r\noups.com&gt; \nSent: Sunday, 5 May 2013 10:59 PM\nSubject: [vedic-wisdom] Re: Co=\r\nmparing Dasavataras!\n\n=C2=A0 \nDear Rajarshi,\n=C2=A0\nEven Parasara did not s=\r\nay there are just 9 or 10 avataras or that there is a one-to-one correspond=\r\nence to grahas. He too said there are innumerable avataras. Avataras can co=\r\nme with a combination of paramatmamsas (supreme/absolute being portions) an=\r\nd jivatmamsas (living/relative being portions) taken from grahas in any com=\r\nbination. Though 9 main avataras of Vishnu came from paramatmamsas of 9 gra=\r\nhas, many many other avataras also descended on earth due to various other =\r\ncombinations of paramatmamsas and jivatmamsas of the same 9 grahas! There a=\r\nre obviously many possibilities.\n=C2=A0\nIn fact, Parasara says that ALL bei=\r\nngs contain some paramatmamsa and some jivatmamsa, coming from grahas. But =\r\njivatmamsa is predominant in most of us.\n=C2=A0\nWhen one leaves earth, para=\r\nmatmamsas in one return to respective grahas and jivatmamsas take birth aga=\r\nin based on desires. In the &#39;end&#39;, even the jivatmamsas return to respectiv=\r\ne grahas. At the time of Mahapralaya, grahas also merge back in Supreme Lor=\r\nd.\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nAs for Kalki, Parasara did not clarify an=\r\nd we can only speculate. Though some people associate him with lagna, that =\r\nmakes no sense to me either. That is inconsistent with the overall framewor=\r\nk laid by Parasara (i.e. beings born with combinations of paramatmamsas and=\r\n jivatmamsas from *grahas*).\n=C2=A0\nKalki will probably come with paramatma=\r\nmsas of both Sun and Moon. After all, Kalki shows Shiva and Shakti (Sun and=\r\n Moon - soul and mind) coming together finally!! Just a speculation..\n=C2=\r\n=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nWhether you take 9 or 10 or 22 avataras, the th=\r\neory of evolutionary spiritual perfection does not add up because &quot;perfecti=\r\non&quot; occurred before the last avatara, unless you break away from main scrip=\r\ntures and throw away Buddha (and discount Kalki as he has not come yet).\n=\r\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nRather than &quot;evolution&quot;, it is a matter of w=\r\nhat the world needs at that time. If people at the beginning of Satya yuga =\r\nare established in Self always and the only issue is that a small attachmen=\r\nt may develop now and then, disturbing that state of being established in S=\r\nelf (i.e. stealing of Veda!), then the aspect of consciousness that is rele=\r\nvant is &quot;spirit of detachment&quot; (Ketu). If invoked, it removes that attachme=\r\nnt and takes one back to being established in Self. So an avatara correspon=\r\nding to Ketu occurred.\n=C2=A0\nAs collective consciousness became denser, be=\r\ning established in Self became less natural and more effort was needed. So =\r\nthe &quot;spirit of patience, persistence and hard-work&quot; (Saturn) became relevan=\r\nt and an avatara corresponding to Saturn occurred. And so on.\n=C2=A0\nIn the=\r\n dark ages of Kali yuga, rational minds wouldn&#39;t accept anything that didn&#39;=\r\nt &quot;make sense&quot;. Being established in Self became an unnatural, ridiculous a=\r\nnd incomprehensible notion. So the &quot;spirit of comprehension&quot; (Mercury) beca=\r\nme relevant. An avatara corresponding to Mercury occurred and tried to expl=\r\nain being established in Self as a comprehensible notion, so that rational =\r\nminds of that age would accept it to an extent and attempt it.\n=C2=A0\nAvata=\r\nras occur based on the needs of collective consciousness. Of course, if one=\r\n&#39;s consciousness is in a different state from the collective consciousness =\r\nof that time, the current avatara may not be relevant to one.\n=C2=A0\n