asa, explicitly mentioned =\r\nthat Rama, Krishna, Narasimha and Varaha are &quot;poornavataras&quot; (used that exa=\r\nct expression) while other avataras have some amount of jivatmamsa too (tho=\r\nugh paramatmamsa dominates jivatmamsa).\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Secondly, after describing=\r\n the avataras, SB says that there are in fact innumerable avataras and that=\r\n all rishis, munis, manus, demigods etc are avataras of Supreme Lord. It is=\r\n under THAT context that 1.3.28 then proceeds to say &quot;these avataras are pa=\r\nrtial, while Krishna is Lord Himself.&quot; I question if the deduction that Kri=\r\nshna *alone* is Lord Himself and Rama is not is accurate! It only seems to =\r\nsay that all these rishis, manus, demigods etc are partial. As I said above=\r\n, Pararsara explicitly said that both Rama and Krishna are poornavataras.\n&gt;=\r\n=C2=A0\n&gt;Third, let us ask a very fundamental question: What exactly does it=\r\n mean if an avatara is &quot;Lord Himself&quot;?\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;W=\r\nhile SB talks of Krishna being &quot;Lord Himself&quot; in 1.3.28, it also says in 1.=\r\n3.30: &quot;forms of Supreme Lord, who is in reality formless (arUpa) and of the=\r\n nature of pure consciousness (chidAtman), are manufactured by the qualitie=\r\ns of Maya&quot;. In the next verse, it further compares forms of Lord to clouds =\r\nin sky and dirt in air. Just as sky *contains* clouds and is beyond them, s=\r\nimilarly Lord *contains* forms and is beyond them. So, again, what is the m=\r\neaning of a specific form that descended on earth being &quot;Lord Himself&quot;? I a=\r\nm afraid people may be misinterpreting this notion based on their fancies a=\r\nnd conditioning..\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;All beings are made up of paramatma (supreme/abs=\r\nolute being) and jivatma (living/relative being). The latter portion is dom=\r\ninant in us and is responsible for desires and rebirth. Great avataras desc=\r\nend from a higher portion of paramatma. Very rarely avataras descend entire=\r\nly from paramatma without ANY jivatma portion. Rama and Krishna are specifi=\r\nc examples given by Parasara.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;They are entirely divine, but they d=\r\no not encapsulate the entire divinity!!!! After all, &quot;entire divinity&quot; cann=\r\not be encapsulated by any form just as no cloud can contain the entire sky.=\r\n They take part in the drama obeying and executing the divine will but NOT =\r\naltering it. This applies to Krishna as well as Rama.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;*=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0 *\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;&gt; Buddha was great spiritual force in this world. But I do n=\r\not\n&gt;&gt; see him fit in the scheme of evolutionary Avatars. His\n&gt;&gt; realization=\r\n, the one he advocated, is a static realization,\n&gt;&gt; an end in a void.\n&gt;=C2=\r\n=A0\n&gt;First, he IS mentioned in SB list of avataras as well as Parasara&#39;s li=\r\nst. If he does not &quot;fit&quot; in your &quot;scheme of evolutionary Avatars&quot;, then you=\r\nr concept is possibly wrong and avataras are perhaps not &quot;evolutionary&quot; as =\r\nyou theorize.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Secondly, as per Parasara, Buddha corresponds to Mer=\r\ncury, who personifies logical mind and the spirit of investigation and comp=\r\nrehension. Logical mind and its spirit of comprehension are inherently fall=\r\nible. Even a perfected spirit of comprehension is not capable of grasping t=\r\nhe Absolute Reality completely, for it is beyond comprehension. So, no wond=\r\ner it simplifies the Incomprehensible in an attempt to comprehend! That is =\r\nwhat Buddha ended up doing. However, logical mind has a great appeal in the=\r\n Age of Reason in this Kali yuga. No wonder Buddha was/is/will be a great s=\r\npiritual force in this world in this age.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=