out it, perfec=\r\nted mind (paramatma aspect represented by Moon) and soul (paramatma aspect =\r\nrepresented by Sun) are not really that different. So I am afraid Krishna a=\r\nnd Rama are not that different, though the specifics of their stories may b=\r\ne different.\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;One last word though. If someone truly believes that =\r\nKrishna is superior to Rama and worships Krishna (or vice versa!), I am ver=\r\ny happy for such a person. My arguments are more for the sake of sharing th=\r\ninking/knowledge and pushing the boundaries of understanding in the long ru=\r\nn, than changing the minds of anyone in the short run. In the end, everyone=\r\n of us will have to go through one&#39;s own cycles of various tamasik, rajasik=\r\n and saattwik stages of evolution before one starts grasping some fistfuls =\r\nof Reality. These concepts are too subtle for anyone to convince others or =\r\nbe absolutely confident oneself!\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;Krishnarpanamastu, Narasimha ----=\r\n---- Astrology & Spirituality Resources: http://www.vedicastrologer.org/\n&gt;-=\r\n-------\n&gt;\n&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;&gt;________________________________\n&gt;&gt;From: rajarshi n=\r\nandy &lt;rajarshi14@...&gt;\n&gt;&gt;To: &quot;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com&quot; &lt;vedic-w=\r\nisdom@yahoogroups.com&gt; \n&gt;&gt;Sent: Saturday, May 4, 2013 7:34 AM\n&gt;&gt;Subject: Re=\r\n: [vedic-wisdom] Comparing Dasavataras!\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;=C2=A0 \n&gt;&gt;Namaste,\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;=\r\n\n&gt;&gt;Jai Ma!\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;I have a different view point. Let me write down as I=\r\n see it, in point by point manner.\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;1. In the Bhagwata Purana, there=\r\n are a list of 22 Avataras of Vishnu. In this list of 22, Varaha Avatara is=\r\n the 2nd Avatara, and Matsya is the 10th Avatara. Dattatreya, Nara-narayana=\r\n,Vyasa Deva himself are in this list, and then the Bhagawata Purana goes on=\r\ntu mention that the Avatars of Vishnu are innumerable. In the 10th Canto, V=\r\nyasa says all these Avatars, and innumerable others, are amsas of the Supre=\r\nme Being while Krshna is &quot;swayam Bhagawan.&quot;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;2. Of these various pos=\r\nsible Avataras, 10, or rather 9 as I believe, are/have been accorded specia=\r\nl mention and significance across various Hindu spiritual literature, speci=\r\nally those which were composed in the Kali-Yuga, namely the Puranas.[When K=\r\nrshna was alive, it was Kali-Sandhya, his physical presence had curtailed t=\r\nhe full effect of Kali,once he left his body, Kali started in full flow. Al=\r\nl Puranas were composed after this, hence these are scriptures of the Kali-=\r\nYuga, as are Tantras]\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;3. These 10/9 Avataras have a fixed sequence =\r\nof appearance. Matysa, Kurma, Varaha, Narasimha, Vamana, Parashurama, Rama,=\r\n Krshna, (Buddha) and Kalki. There is an unmistakeable connection of the fo=\r\nrm and sequence of these main avatars with the evolution of life on earth. =\r\nFrom the aquatic, to the amphibian, to the land-animal, to the half-animal-=\r\nhalf-man, to the dwarf man (first human life form who immediately takes pos=\r\nsession of this earth represented by Vamana&#39;s 3 steps), to the Rajashik ava=\r\ntara of Parashurama moving around with an axe, to the Sattwa Guna Avatara o=\r\nf Rama, to the Nirguna Avatara of Krshna. Also, this indicates that spiritu=\r\nality is not to be separated into another world, but is a progressive reali=\r\nzation of the various manifestation and potentials that lie inherent in the=\r\n consciousness and its development through various life-forms. Larger spiri=\r\ntuality of earth and evolution go hand in hand. That is Nature&#39;s grand desi=\r\ngn for life on earth.\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;4. In this specifc context, I am only focusin=\r\ng on the parable of these main 9/10 Avatars. It is not my contention that i=\r\nf one worships say Matysa Avatara, one will not attain to a state of libera=\r\ntion of the soul. As is the nature of spiritual cosmology in Hinduism, any =\r\nDevata can lead a person to any depth of realization. And each one of the A=\r\nvatars of Vishnu are self-realized in their own way and can be consider sup=\r\ner-massive spiritual dynamos.\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;=C2=A05. Of these, naturally, Rama=\r\n and Krshna are most adored because they represent a stage of evolution, bo=\r\nth inside as well as outside, which society can relate of much easier, in t=\r\nhis age. Rama represents, for me, the stage of most satwic mind. A satwic m=\r\nind is in control of itself. It known how to transform the animal tendencie=\r\ns within and without - monkeys - into a constructive force for a greater pu=\r\nrpose. However, as with a state of full Sattwa Guna, there can be instances=\r\n, even though few, of dejection. For it is static in nature and will change=\r\n only when circumstances force it to. As per the Valmiki Ramayana, Rama did=\r\n feel dejected while searching for Sita in the forest. He did have a moment=\r\ns fear before the final assault on Ravana, which was dispelled by Agsatha w=\r\nhen the later revealed the stotra of the Sun to Rama. At the end of the fin=\r\nal battle, Rama tells Sita, in a most dispassionate manner, that he killed =\r\nRavana not to rescue her, but it was\n the Dharma to do so, and to unhold hi=\r\ns family honour. That too was the dharma of that age when he lived, family =\r\nhonor. The way I look at this grand epic, and I bow humbly to the genius of=\r\n Rishis Valmiki for representing the things as they are, as a scribe, as a =\r\npoet, as an observer, and not adding his own preferences to it anywhere, in=\r\n the 14 years of tribulation that Rama faced which culminated into his kill=\r\ning Ravana, he changed into the most dispassionate leader, such that no per=\r\nsonal consideration or emotions or passions can overturn the Rajadharma. Hi=\r\ns life is a lesson of what a true leader must be! Krshna, OTOH, had this im=\r\nmaculate detachment right from birth. I am not taking his=C2=A0 supernatura=\r\nl feats into account. It is his singular and constant detachment from situa=\r\ntions, from people, from environment, from circumstances that mark his life=\r\n. At the age of eight, he decides to leave Vrindavana for Mathura. All his =\r\nfriends, his foster parents, his\n village-folks who so loved him, pleaded w=\r\nith him that it would make no sense for him to leave the shelter, love and =\r\ncomfort of his happy, settled village life and head into an unknown destiny=\r\n and destination. Krshna tried to reason with them, then he understood that=\r\n they won&#39;t understand, he promised he will return back once his work in Ma=\r\nthura is over. He never returned. Later, much later, when the Gopis came to=\r\n him asking him to participate in their dance, he obliged. But the moment s=\r\nome of them started getting jealous and possessive of Krshna, he removed hi=\r\nmself quietly from the scene, saying that he belongs to everyone equally an=\r\nd no one has any special right over him. When Shishupala abused Krshna, the=\r\n later merely kept dropping flowers on the floor, smiling and counting. The=\r\n moment the 100th abuse was over, he swiftly cut off Shishupala&#39;s head and =\r\nwas back into his poise. But when Bhurishrava unfairly accused Krshna of be=\r\ning a revolutionist and\n charlatan, Krshna did not kill him. When Duryodhan=\r\na, who used to think of Krshna as another black magician, wanted to arrest =\r\nhim, Krshna showed his vikarala roopa in the assembly of kings, yet he did =\r\nnot finish the enemies off. The very next moment he was back into his own p=\r\noised self. Never in the whole Mahabharata is there one instance of his goi=\r\nng overboard, never a single shade of depression, equivocation, or lack of =\r\nconfidence in his actions, irrespective of what others say or think of him.=\r\n And then right in the middle of the greatest war he had the perfect equipo=\r\nise to deliver the most sublime spiritual philosophy. That is why his life =\r\nremains the best ideal of Karma-Yoga. For a true Karma-Yogi by definition c=\r\nan never be dejected. It is impossible. Neither the action nor the results =\r\nbelong to the instrument. When running away from the battle-field and killi=\r\nng Kaliya Yavana, or when advising Bheema to tear apart Jarashanda, or gest=\r\nuring Bheema to\n hit Duryodhana below the waist, or getting Shikhandi to fa=\r\nce Bhisma, Krshna, as if by some Divine Intuition, knew exactly how the sit=\r\nuations must be lined up which would cause the destruction of these people.=\r\n This kind of knowledge cannot come by the rational thinking. But happens w=\r\nhen one is constantly and consciously connected to the Universal Force. We =\r\ndo not find these kind of complex situations in the Rama Avatara, at least =\r\nin the Valmiki Ramayana. Of course, if we take the Adhbut Ramayana or such =\r\nother auxilliary texts and retelling, we get a different picture. In the Ad=\r\nbhuta Ramayana we have a 1000 headed demon attacking Rama after he kills Ra=\r\nvana, and then Sita turns into Adya Shakti and demolishes the 1000 headed d=\r\nemon and Rama worships her. But if we take only the Ramayana and the Mahabh=\r\narata, the picture that emerges is very clear. Rama is the embodiment of Sa=\r\nttwic mind. Therefore he displays all the great characteristics of satwa, c=\r\nhief of\n which is self-control, as well as the occasional sadness caused du=\r\ne to separation from his wife Sita whom, at least until Ravana was destroye=\r\nd, he loved very dearly. Satwa guna creates a true saint, but can also caus=\r\ne some grief when the stability is shaken. Krshna was gunatita. He had no a=\r\nttachment to anything in this world - man, women, deva, danava, friend, ene=\r\nmy - and therefore he was never affected any trace of negative emotion. His=\r\n Ananda never left him even in the most trying situations. 6. Buddha was gr=\r\neat spiritual force in this world. But I do not see him fit in the scheme o=\r\nf evolutionary Avatars. His realization, the one he advocated, is a static =\r\nrealization, an end in a void. This is clearly denying of the reality of th=\r\nis earth. I find this not in tune with what either Rama or Krshna espoused.=\r\n None of them negated this world. If negation of this world and life is the=\r\n final aim, then why send so many avatars at crucial stages of evolutionary=\r\n\n development? If the spiritual impact on masses is the reason for Buddha b=\r\neing an Avatara, then why not Jesus or Zorathrusta.? They are no less impac=\r\ntful in that sense. But do they fit in the scheme of spiritual line that th=\r\nese 9 Avataras of Narayana indicate in a most logical manner? No. As such m=\r\nany vaishnava traditions in parts of India, do not consider Buddha to be an=\r\n avatara. Realization, to be complete and holistic, must be both static and=\r\n dynamic, outside of life as well as inside of life. That is why the Tantra=\r\ns formed their own kind of spiritual philosophy, of the world as body of Sh=\r\nakti and therefore an object of reverence and realization. 7. The original =\r\nliterature of the Nath Yogis used to mention 9 chakras. These are centers o=\r\nf psychological functions. 6 inside the human body and 3 too subtle, or non=\r\n-developed in most people, even seekers. It is my belief that each of the 9=\r\n Avataras - excluding Buddha - correspond to the full power and force\n of o=\r\nne of these 9 Chakras. Similarly, the 9 grahas, or that which can modify co=\r\nnsciousness or allow the consciousness to explore and express itself is var=\r\nious possiblities, are 9 in number. The lagna is a reference point and not =\r\na graha. Therefore the chief Avatars who represent the parable of evolution=\r\n are nine in number. And the ninth of the sequence is yet to come. 8. I can=\r\nnot comment on which graha would typically represent which Avatara. I know =\r\nof what the BPHS says, however, it is my belief - feel free to disagree wit=\r\nh it -:)[one cannot rule out some deep-rooted corruption of understanding o=\r\nr textual misrepresentation in this Kali-Yuga] - that the Atmah among the A=\r\nvataras has not yet appeared. It will be Kalki, or as Vimalananda seems to =\r\nsay in the Aghora books, Nishkalanka - the stainless one. There is only one=\r\n thing which is perfectly stainless, the Atmah .After a Nirguna/Gunatita aw=\r\nastha comes living in the full and complete purity and might\n and force and=\r\n strength of the Atmah. By the sheer dint of his purity the last Avatara wi=\r\nll burn away opposing forces of this world and fulfill the purpose of evolu=\r\ntion. Even Krshna used diplomacy at various points in his adult life to ach=\r\nieve his ends. Kalki, I am speculating, won&#39;t even need that. The white hor=\r\nse and that sword is a metaphor. He will be the only one capable enough to =\r\nrectify the various errors and corruptions that beset our age. Well, this i=\r\ns how I look at the story of Avataras. It is perfectly ok not to agree with=\r\n my views, but I am reasonably sanguine now that this is what is closer to =\r\ntruth. -Regards =C2=A0Rajarshi\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;awaktam wyaktimApannam manyantE mAma=\r\nbuddhayah |param bhAwamajAnanto mamAwyayamanuttamam ||[7:24]\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;___=\r\n_____________________________\n&gt;&gt;From: Narasimha P.V.R. Rao &lt;pvr108@...=\r\nm&gt;\n&gt;&gt;To: Vedic Wisdom &lt;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com&gt; \n&gt;&gt;Sent: Thursday, 25 =\r\nApril 2013 9:00 AM\n&gt;&gt;Subject: [vedic-wisdom] Comparing Dasavataras!\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;=\r\n&gt;\n&gt;&gt;=C2=A0 \n&gt;&gt;Namaste friends, =C2=A0 There was a discussion on Lord Vishnu=\r\n&#39;s Dasavataras on a limited access forum on Facebook. A learned friend wrot=\r\ne that &quot;Krshna is the God-man&quot;, &quot;Previous Avatars are a build-up to this st=\r\nage&quot; and &quot;Buddha after Krshna is like going back from the linear progressio=\r\nn of spirituality that the Avatars manifest one after the other upto Krshna=\r\n&quot;. =C2=A0 I want to emphatically disagree with this notion that Dasavatars =\r\nof a &quot;linear progression of spirituality..upto Krshna&quot;. =C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0 * =C2=A0 Each avatara represents an aspect of Supreme in a perfected fo=\r\nrm. =C2=A0 Maharshi Parasara equated dasavataras with planets. For example,=\r\n Rama, Krishna and Narasimha are Sun, Moon and Mars, respectively. =C2=A0 W=\r\ne also know that Sun, Moon, Mars, Mercury, Jupiter, Venus, Saturn, Rahu and=\r\n Ketu are personifications of soul, mind, energy/initiative/drive, learning=\r\n spirit, wisdom/discrimination, spirit of enjoyment/being happy, patience/d=\r\niscipline,\n spirit of innovation/breaking barriers and detachment (respecti=\r\nvely). =C2=A0 Correspondingly, each avatara is an expression of that aspect=\r\n of Supreme in a perfected form. Each story is an example of how that aspec=\r\nt operates. =C2=A0 Lord Rama&#39;s story is a perfected example of how soul ope=\r\nrates. Lord Krishna&#39;s story is a perfected example of how mind operates. Lo=\r\nrd Vamana&#39;s story is a perfected example of how wisdom/discrimination opera=\r\ntes. Lord Narasimha&#39;s story is a perfected example of how energy/drive/init=\r\niative operates. =C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * =C2=A0 Now, let us remember one basi=\r\nc thing. Soul in us, mind in us, energy in us, learning spirit in us, wisdo=\r\nm in us, happiness in us, discipline/patience in us - all these are differe=\r\nnt manifestations of the same Self. However, when Self manifests as these d=\r\nifferent aspects, it has different qualities and plays different roles. The=\r\nre is no comparison between them. =C2=A0 We MAY focus on one aspect of us f=\r\nirst,\n perfect it and then perfect other aspects through it. But, we need b=\r\nalance between all aspects in the end. Similarly, these different aspects o=\r\nf Supreme Being are incomparable and are in a balance working together in t=\r\nhe Cosmos. =C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * =C2=A0 One who is fascinated by the qualit=\r\nies of soul may like the story that demonstrates how soul operates; one who=\r\n is fascinated by the qualities of mind may like the story that demonstrate=\r\ns how mind operates, and one who is fascinated by the qualities of wisdom m=\r\nay like the story that demonstrates how wisdom operates. And so on. But thi=\r\ns is just a matter of taste and subjective preference. =C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 =\r\n* =C2=A0 Let us focus on Rama and Krishna, i.e. soul and mind. Soul is seen=\r\n as a representative of god in us, because of some basic attributes of it. =\r\nIt is the higher self and has no agendas, no likes or dislikes. =C2=A0 Once=\r\n mind fancies a separate existence with some\n agendas/desires, soul support=\r\ns the individualized consciousness stemming from that fancy and sees it as =\r\nits dharma. It lends strength and support to EVERY aspect of this individua=\r\nlized consciousness (e.g. mind, energy, intellect, learning ability, enjoym=\r\nent, discipline etc). It supports them fully and yet has no desires/agendas=\r\n/likes/dislikes of its own! It impassionately witnesses and records all of =\r\none&#39;s agendas and karmas so that Laws of Nature give proper fruits later on=\r\n. It does all that despite full awareness that it is neither doing those ka=\r\nrmas nor receiving the fruits. As mind and other aspects of the individuali=\r\nzed consciousness entertain the notion that they are doing things and beget=\r\nting the fruits, soul supports them fully in this play. It sees that as its=\r\n dharma and does it impassionately. =C2=A0 Now, does this sound exciting? P=\r\nerhaps not to all. This functionality of an impassionate witness supporting=\r\n the play, may not seem interesting enough\n to some. =C2=A0 On the other ha=\r\nnd, mind has likes, dislikes and agendas. It is constantly pursuing those a=\r\ngendas, getting things and achieving things. Movement of mind is what keeps=\r\n the individualization going!!! Though soul is the support for everything e=\r\nlse in the individualized consciousness, soul is a witness doing its dharma=\r\n impassionately. It is mind that keeps the individualization going and brin=\r\ngs in agendas and passion and even decides/affects every entity&#39;s dharma. T=\r\nhat way, mind is really the &quot;boss&quot; of the individualization. No wonder Kris=\r\nhna&#39;s life appeals more to one who may be excited by this description! =C2=\r\n=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * =C2=A0 Lord Krishna is obviously awe-inspiring, but le=\r\nt me put Rama&#39;s life in perspective. =C2=A0 Rama&#39;s life demonstrates how so=\r\nul operates. At a young age, he received Brahma Jnana from Vasishtha and be=\r\ncame realized. Yet, he did whatever was his &quot;dharma&quot;. He helped Vishwamitra=\r\n. Soon after marriage, he was given\n kingdom. At the last moment, his fathe=\r\nr banished him to forest at the behest of his step-mother and his step-brot=\r\nher was given the throne. He had no complaints. Though his father, step-mot=\r\nher and step-brother felt guilty to various degrees, he himself supported a=\r\nnd consoled all three and followed his dharma impassionately. Though he kne=\r\nw leaving Sita in the forest with Lakshmana and going after the golden deer=\r\n would cause problems, he did it impassionately when Sita insisted. When sh=\r\ne was kidnapped by Ravana, he searched for her and fought the battle. He ne=\r\nver faulted Sita for forcing him to leave her or faulted Lakshmana for leav=\r\ning her later. He accepted every life situation with no complaints and did =\r\nthe best possible action then. Even as he killed Ravana, he did so without =\r\nhatred or anger, but as his impassionate dharma. Even as Ravana was dying, =\r\nhe went to him and respectfully learned some subjects that were going to di=\r\nsappear with Ravana! =C2=A0 Rama\n is a perfect example of a liberated man w=\r\nith no desires or agendas who impassionately discharges one&#39;s dharma arisin=\r\ng from the momentum of karmas before liberation. THAT is basically what sou=\r\nl does! =C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * =C2=A0 As another example, let us look at Lor=\r\nd Vaamana. His story is a perfect demonstration of how wisdom/discriminatio=\r\nn operates. =C2=A0 He was born as a learned pygmy. He filled the entire cos=\r\nmos to rid earth of a charitable demon king with many great qualities. =C2=\r\n=A0 Wisdom/discrimination makes one humble and unassuming. When one is doin=\r\ng good work but tainted with demonic qualities (e.g. pride or attachment), =\r\none&#39;s discrimination is not pleased until that pride is suppressed. When wi=\r\nsdom fills one&#39;s entire consciousness, then demonic qualities are completel=\r\ny suppressed. =C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 * =C2=A0 Please think about the other ava=\r\ntaras. The stories can be understood as perfect demonstrations of how vario=\r\nus aspects of\n our consciousness operate, based on clues from Maharshi Para=\r\nsara. =C2=A0 Let us not compare Dasavataras, but celebrate each of them sep=\r\narately. Of course, if you are more attracted to one of them, please think =\r\nabout that avatara more and develop devotion. They are ALL capable 