that he/she has some form o=\r\nf power or influence in this world in any sphere.&nbsp;Rama had no malice f=\r\nor anyone. Not even Ravana, by the end of the war at least. He was the very=\r\n personification of Satwa. In Satwa, conflict and malice and cunningness ar=\r\ne impossible.&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;div style=3D&quot;BACKGROUND-COLOR: transparent; FONT-STYLE=\r\n: normal; FONT-FAMILY: Courier New, courier, monaco, monospace, sans-serif;=\r\n COLOR: rgb(0,0,0); FONT-SIZE: 16px; RIGHT: auto&quot;&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;div style=\r\n=3D&quot;BACKGROUND-COLOR: transparent; FONT-STYLE: normal; FONT-FAMILY: Courier=\r\n New, courier, monaco, monospace, sans-serif; COLOR: rgb(0,0,0); FONT-SIZE:=\r\n 16px; RIGHT: auto&quot;&gt;Recently, a friend of mine told me that he has learnt a=\r\nll his life that one must listen to Krshna&#39;s advice, but only follow what R=\r\nama did, and not what Krshna did. I disagree with this vehemently. If one r=\r\neads entire Krshna&#39;s life&nbsp;with an objective mind, Krshna of Vrndavana,=\r\n Krshna of Mathura, Krshna of Kurushetra, Krshna the Jagat Guru who speaks =\r\nthe Gita, one will find that what Krshna the Guru adviced in the Gita,&nbsp=\r\n;Krshna the&nbsp;Divine Worker&nbsp;himself followed it all through his lif=\r\ne at every instance. It is his&nbsp;perfect detachment under all circumstan=\r\nces of life, from childhood&nbsp;to his death,&nbsp;that makes me wonder, w=\r\nas this a man or was this a God? Can a man even do something like this? It =\r\nis as if there is a part of Krshna who is always separate\n from everything,=\r\n and silently watches the whole scene with a bemused smile. He had not a si=\r\nngle personal stake in the Mahabharata. Rama at least had his wife abducted=\r\n for him to start a war against Ravana. But Krshna had zero&nbsp;personal s=\r\ntake in the Mahabharata.&nbsp;After liberating his parents from Kamsa, very=\r\n soon he went off to meet the Pandavas. From out of nowhere he forced himse